blocks.value: A pilot randomized controlled trial examining the impact of asleep intervention targeting home routines on young children's (3-6 years) physical activity

Background: Given evidence suggesting that sleep impacts on metabolic processes, interventions targeting sleep may improve child physical activity (PA).
Objectives: To describe the potential effect of an intervention to increase sleep on young children's (3-6 years) moderate to vigorous PA (MVPA) and total PA. To determine adherence to the intervention, impact on sleep duration as well as feasibility, uptake and acceptability was also assessed.
Methods: Pilot randomized controlled trial with 76 parent-child dyads randomly allocated to an intervention (n = 38) or control group (n = 38). Parents in the intervention group received a 3-month theory-informed intervention consisting of an online video, a telephone call and two text messages. Child PA was assessed using accelerometers at baseline and approximately 3 months. Parents also completed asleep log and a telephone interview.
Results: The consent rate was 41% (76/186). Estimated effect size for the intervention relative to control was 10.8 min/day for MVPA, 2.7 min/day for PA and 0.9 h for sleep. Sixteen (44%) parents accessed the video, and 18 (50%) received the telephone call. Over 40% of parents found the video and telephone call useful/very useful.
Conclusions: This study reports promising effects that an intervention targeting sleep may improve child MVPA and sleep duration. Some modifications to data collection methods and intervention delivery are needed.

Inadequate physical activity (PA) is associated with the most prevalent causes of mortality and morbidity in Australia, including obesity. Childhood is a critical period to establish physically active behaviours (2), with PA levels in childhood reported to predict activity levels in later life. Moderate to vigorous physical activity (MVPA) in particular is shown to prevent metabolic syndrome and obesity. International and population guidelines from various developed countries including Australia, USA and the UK recommend that young children spend at least 180 min in PA, of which 60 min is MVPA. Internationally, however, studies using objective measures of PA report that less than 10% meet these guidelines. Previous systematic reviews of interventions to improve PA in children aged 2 to 5 years however have reported only small to moderate effects on child PA (standardized mean difference: 0.44; 95% confidence interval [CI]: 0.12-0.76). As such, strategies to enhance the efficacy of current PA interventions are needed.
Recent reviews have outlined the importance of considering PA alongside other movement behaviours, such as sleep, in attempts to improve the health and PA of young children. A number of systematic reviews of mainly cross-sectional studies also report a possible association between sleep and obesityrelated risk factors including PA in young children. Randomized experimental designs however are needed to test whether a causal relationship exists between sleep and PA.
To our knowledge, only one experimental trial exists. This study used a randomized cross-over trial design where 37 school-aged children (8-11 years old) were allocated to increase or reduce sleep by 1.5 h per night for 1 week. The study found that children with shorter sleep duration had decreased mean PA levels and higher television viewing time, but no difference in MVPA relative to increased sleep duration. Limitations of the study include using self-reported measures of MVPA, and the prescription of asleep protocol which is unlikely to be sustained in the long term. Further studies assessing the potential relationship of targeting sleep on child PA are needed.
Therefore, this pilot randomized controlled trial (RCT) seeks to describe the effect size of an intervention to support parents to modify household routines to increase child sleep duration on child MVPA and total PA. We also assessed the impact of the intervention on sleep, as well as report on feasibility and acceptability of the intervention. We hypothesize that children receiving the sleep intervention will have higher levels of MVPA and total PA than children in the control arm.
This trial was prospectively registered with the Australian New Zealand Clinical Trials Registry (ACTRN12616000822482) and follows the CON-SORT reporting guidelines for pilot studies.

This study utilized an RCT design with 76 parentchildren dyads. Parents whose 3 to 6-year-old children attended a convenience sample of centre-based childcare centres (including preschools and long daycare centres) in the Hunter New England region of New South Wales, Australia were approached to participate in the study.
Hunter New England Human Research Ethics Committee (reference number 15/11/18/4.03) and the University of Newcastle Hunter New England Human Research Ethics Committee (reference number H-2016-0088).

Nine childcare services provided consent for researchers to visit the service for 1 week at baseline to recruit participants and undertake data collection.
Children were eligible if they were aged between 3 and 6 years, attended childcare during the week of baseline data collection and did not have any significant conditions preventing PA participation. Children up to 6 years old were included as childcare services in Australia enrol children up to age six. We anticipate that children attending childcare services are likely to have different PA patterns to those attending schools. Parents who resided with the child on four or more nights per week were eligible to receive the intervention.
Study information and consent forms were distributed to parents via childcare staff, and by a research assistant (RA) during periods of drop-off or pick-up the week prior to the baseline data collection. Parents consented to having their child's PA measured via waist accelerometer for 7 days, complete a 7-day activity/sleep log for their child (including when the accelerometer was not worn), receive text message reminders to fit the accelerometer and complete a telephone survey.

Following baseline data collection, dyads were randomized to the intervention or control group in a 1:1 ratio via block randomization (block size ranged between 2 and 6), using a central concealed random allocation process by a blinded statistician. RAs undertaking data collection were blinded to group allocation.

The intervention was developed by the researchers and a trusted child health and parenting organization with over 20 years' experience delivering evidencebased parenting programs. The intervention was based on best practice systematic review evidence and recommendations from peak sleep (i.e. American Academy of Sleep and Sleep Health Foundation) organizations. Intervention content was informed by the theory of planned behaviour and targeted parent's beliefs associated with their attitudes, subjective norms and perceived behavioural control related to sleep. The strategies included (i) having age appropriate bed-and day-time routines; (ii) removing distractions before bed; (iii) allowing child to self-sooth; and (iv) making concrete changes in household routines.
Specifically, between August and November 2016, parents received the following: a) Online video: Parents received a welcome email with a link to a pre-recorded video. The video was 12 min long and included a mix of visual and verbal instructions to enhance reflection on current beliefs and practices related to their child's sleep. The content targeted key behavioural, normative and control beliefs in relation to implementing recommended sleep practices. The video provided brief information about the benefits of sleep, the recommended amount of sleep for young children, discussed developmental changes in sleep patterns in young children (i.e. naps) and outlined key practical changes that could be implemented to promote healthy sleep. The video provided specific recommendations on how to implement routines conducive to sleep and provided concrete, practical tips for establishing pre and post bed-time routines. Lastly, the video outlined information for parents on how to incorporate these into their child's routines and how to deal with introducing such changes. Where participants had not accessed the video link within a week of it being sent, participants received one email reminder. b) Telephone call: Approximately 2 to 4 weeks after the video link was emailed, a trained psychologist from the parenting organization rang parents to provide support to implement the messages in the video. The psychologist briefly reiterated messages within the video and used motivational interviewing techniques to support parents to set specific goals for implementing new sleep routines and overcoming identified barriers. Where parents had not accessed the video link, the psychologist provided brief information regarding video content. Up to three attempts were made to reach parents, with up to another three follow-up calls for those parents making contact with the psychologist. c) Text messages: Two text messages were sent approximately 1 week after the phone call. Text messages were tailored to parent's engagement with the intervention and were aimed at encouraging parents to access the video and persist with implementing any new routines that had been put in place.
The control group received link to the online video upon completion of follow-up data collection.
Baseline data was collected between August and October 2016, with follow-up data collection undertaken approximately 3 months post-baseline (November 2016-January 2017).
Parents completed a computer assisted telephone interview reporting on their own demographic characteristics (age, sex, employment status, educational attainment) and child age and sex.

Minutes per day spent in MVPA and PA was collected using a hip-worn accelerometer (Actigraph GT3X+), the gold standard for assessment of PA. RAs showed parents how to fit the accelerometers on their child. The accelerometers were placed above the left iliac crest at the hip of the child using a clip or band.
Parents were requested to fit the accelerometer to their child everyday for 7 days during waking hours. Consistent with recommendations, only children with at least three valid days of accelerometer data (i.e. 18 h) were included in the analyses. Minutes of MVPA and total PA per day were determined using age-specific child-validated equations. Child total sleep duration per day was also assessed with a 7-day activity/sleep log. Parents were asked to document the times when their child was asleep (for both naps and nighttime sleep). Previous research indicates that parent-completed logs for sleep are significantly correlated with Actigraphy measurement (p < 0.001), with an R 2 of 0.57.

Parent-child recruitment, consent and retention rate Of the 189 parents assessed, 186 (98%) were invited to participate. Of these, 76 (41%) parents consented to participate. At follow-up, 49% (n = 37; 95% CI 38.0, 60.0) completed accelerometer data, 34% (n = 26; 95% CI 25.0, 45.0) completed the sleep log and 74% (n = 56; 95% CI 63.0, 83.0) completed the computer assisted telephone interview. There were no significant differences in child age or gender among participants that did and not provide each of the follow-up measures.
Intervention delivery: All parents were emailed a weblink to access the online video. Participants were contacted via telephone and sent the two text messages regardless of whether they had accessed the video. Sixteen (44%) accessed the online video, and 18 (50%) received a call from the psychologist. Fourteen (39%) parents were contactable on the first call attempt, 9 (25%) parents required a second call attempt and 13 (36%) parents required a third call attempt. Nine (25%) parents did not answer any of these calls and did not receive any further phone contact. Of those parents answering at least one call attempt (n = 27), four (15%) parents required one follow-up, two (7%) parents required a two follow-up calls and eight (30%) parents received a third and final follow-up call. The most common reason for not delivering the call was due to parents not answering phone calls.
Thirty-four parents (92%) were sent both text messages. Of those that were not sent text messages, three did not provide mobile numbers and one opted out from receiving text messages. Ten parents (27%) received all components of the intervention as intended (i.e. watched the entire video, received the phone call and all text messages).

Intervention delivery was monitored using internal data collection form. The following information was recorded for each participant: date weblink sent, dates of calls (up to three) and whether a message was left, date call was completed, reasons for non-completion of calls and dates when each text message was sent.

Intervention uptake: Of the 16 (42%) parents who accessed the online video, 13 (81%) watched the entire video and 2 (13%) watched approximately half of the video. Bedtime routines implemented or planned to be implemented by parents, and barriers to watching the video were the most commonly discussed topics. One (4%; 95% CI 0.7, 18.9), five (19%; 95% CI 8.5, 37.9) and nine (35%; 95% CI 15.0, 54.2) parents reported not receiving the link to the video, telephone call and text messages, respectively.
Intervention acceptability: Overall, 17 (65%; 95% CI 46.2, 80.6) parents in the intervention arm rated the intervention as good. Of those who completed the Pilot of asleep intervention on child activity | 5 of 8 survey and received the intervention, 12 (46%; 95% CI 28.8, 64.5) found the video useful or very useful, 11 (42%; 95% CI 25.5, 61.1) found the telephone call useful or very useful and four (15.4%; 95% CI 6.2, 33.5) found the text messages useful or very useful. In response to an open-ended question, parents commented they found the study 'interesting' and that it was 'good to learn some new things'.

As this is a pilot study, a formal sample size calculation is not required; however, we estimated that approximately 20% of the required number fora definitive trial would be sufficient to provide trends of efficacy and to assess feasibility and acceptability of trial processes. Approximately 500 participants would be required fora definitive trial to detect a clinically significant difference of 10 min in MVPA. This study aimed to recruit 150 child-parent dyads.

All statistical analyses were undertaken in SAS. For all behavioural outcomes (mean MVPA/day, total PA/day and sleep), descriptive statistics including mean (standard deviation) for all continuous outcomes were reported. To estimate effect size, absolute differences between the intervention and control groups, and 95% CIs were reported for all available data. Cohen's effect size was also estimated using post-intervention data only. Statistical testing was undertaken using generalized liner mixed models adjusting for baseline values with intervention group included as an interaction term. Descriptive statistics were provided for all feasibility and acceptability data.

A total of 76 parents took part in the study, with 38 randomized to the intervention and 38 to the control arm (see Fig. for CONSORT diagram). The characteristics of participants were similar across groups for most characteristics (Table).

The intervention produced an effect size of 10.8 min/day (Cohen's effect size = 0.41) for MVPA, 2.7 min/day (Cohen's effect size = 0.22) for PA and 0.9 h/day (Cohen's effect size = 0.43) for sleep (Table).

To our knowledge, this is the first RCT to assess the impact of targeting sleep promoting routines on objectively measured MVPA in 3 to 6 year olds. This pilot study found a small to moderate effect size favouring the intervention for all outcomes, on the basis of Cohen's effect sizes. In contrast, the only other randomized trial with 37 school-aged children found a reduction in child MVPA. Our study utilized an objective measure of MVPA whilst the other study relied on self-report of parents/educators. While the exact mechanisms are unknown, it is possible that increased sleep may impact on factors that influence energy metabolism or reduce fatigue and tiredness, subsequently increasing participation in MVPA.
While the impact of the intervention on child activity and sleep appear promising, data regarding feasibility and acceptability suggests that some modifications to the data collection and intervention procedures maybe needed. Firstly, participant retention rate was variable, with between 34% and 74% completing each measure. The poor retention for some outcomes could be due to the burden of undertaking data collection for parents. Seven days of data collection was chosen to maximize the chance of obtaining three valid days of accelerometer data, as recommended for assessment of PA. It is possible that future data collection attempts could include a shorter period of data collection. Retention rates of approximately 50% however are common in trials to improve PA undertaken in young children. Other methods of collecting sleep data including the use of trackable devices or wrist  accelerometer may also reduce the burden of assessing sleep while increasing validity. Second, only 40% of intervention parents received both the telephone support and viewed the entire video. The current intervention modalities (online, text and telephone) were chosen as they provide wide reach. However, there were considerable challenges with delivering the components of the intervention. Sixteen (21%) parents were unable to be contacted, despite three call attempts and leaving messages. Further, only 15% found the text messages useful. It is possible that scheduling calls after hours or weekends could increase the number of individuals that received the telephone component. Further refinements to the content and modality of the intervention components as well as strategies to maximize uptake of the intervention are needed. This study had a number of limitations. Firstly, a self-reported measure of sleep duration was used, which may have overestimated the impact of the intervention on sleep. We did not use waist accelerometers to assess sleep due to human ethics concern of potential choking in younger children due to longer bands. Secondly, the trial was unable to recruit the planned number of participants (n = 150) due to lower than expected consent rate. Third, only 30% of parents received the full intervention dose despite numerous attempts to contact parents. Lastly, outcomes related to feasibility and acceptability were not included in the trial registration. Nevertheless, this trial provides promising pilot data to support the potential causal relationship sleep duration and MVPA in young children. Future trials using objective measures such as wrist or arm actigraphy, powered to detect significant differences in PA and sleep, which allow examination of the mediating effect of sleep on PA should be undertaken in order to advance efforts to improve PA in young children. Further, the integration of a nested, internal pilot in future definitive trials using similar intervention approaches should be considered given the recommended changes to data collection and intervention methods for this study.
